article.headline: Ely, Zolman key second-half rally
article.linkText: Lady Vols rally to beat Rutgers 59-39
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Rutgers brought attitude, and
second-ranked Tennessee showed some of its own.

Shyra Ely had 18 points and 12 rebounds, and Shanna Zolman added
14 points, including four 3-pointers, to help the Lady Vols beat
Rutgers 59-49 Thursday night.

Tennessee (4-0) trailed by as many as six points in the second
half before Ely found a way to the basket and Zolman scored
seemingly at will from beyond the arc.

While the scoring and hustling on the floor was exciting, there
was just as much drama between plays, including what some Tennessee
players said was good-natured trash talking.

"It was fun. It was a competitive game," Ely said. "They did
challenge us and they might talk trash here and there, but that
gets us going. They can talk trash all they want, but we're going
to perform."

Trailing 38-32 with 12:47 remaining, Tennessee used a 15-8 run
to take a one-point lead.

Ely had three baskets during the spurt, including a backward
flip into the hoop, and Zolman followed with two 3-pointers, the
last giving Tennessee a 47-46 lead with 7:42 to go.

The teams traded the lead twice, but Cappie Pondexter's basket
with 6:28 remaining was Rutgers' last until less than a minute was
left. The Lady Vols scored 12 straight points before the Scarlet
Knights (3-4) got one free throw with about 30 seconds left.

Dawn McCullough led Rutgers with 19 points and Pondexter added
15.

"I wouldn't say trash talking, but we're players. We compete.
We're going to talk ... whether that's to get another player out of
the game mentally. That's all it comes down to," McCullough said.
"They did the same thing. We both talked. We just all competed
tonight."

Tennessee pumped up its defense in the second half while Ashley
Robinson had seven of her career-high eight blocks after halftime.
After one block, she said "not in my house" to the Rutgers
players.

"We showed a different attitude for Tennessee," Robinson said.
"People have said we're soft for about three years now, so we
showed how tough we really can be."

The Scarlet Knights dropped out of this week's poll after losing
their last three games during a brutal 12-day stretch on the road.

"We're all very tired," Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer said.

Rutgers had nine days off to prepare for Tennessee after its
Dec. 6 home game against Temple was postponed due to bad weather.

The Scarlet Knights had a good plan, combining an aggressive
zone defense with a slower offensive style that put the ball in
Pondexter's hands to set up plays in the halfcourt.

"We thought we could win this game," Pondexter said.

Rutgers was ahead 27-25 at halftime after the Lady Vols, who had
scored at least 42 points by halftime in their first three games,
shot only 10-of-29 from the field in the first half mainly because
of Rutgers' zone defense.

Tennessee led in the opening minutes. But Pondexter's driving
layup with 12:56 left put Rutgers up 11-9, and the teams traded the
lead most of the half.

Ely tied it at 25 with a three-point play with 49 seconds left,
and Tennessee had a chance to go ahead when Zolman came up with a
loose ball. But Ely and Robinson missed shots, and Courtney Locke
rebounded for Rutgers. Pondexter missed at the other end, and Locke
got another rebound and passed it to Rebecca Richman for a basket
at the buzzer.
